data1 <- data %>% group_by(StateName) %>% 
  summarize(mean_rat = mean(PatientSurveyStarRating))

# initial plot
ggplot(data1, aes(StateName, mean_rat)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip()

data2filter <- data2 %>% select(FacilityID, State, HCAHPSQuestion, PatientSurveyStarRating) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = HCAHPSQuestion, 
              values_from = PatientSurveyStarRating)

data2comp <- data2filter %>% group_by(State) %>% 
  summarize(mean_rat = mean(`Summary star rating`), 
            mean_rec = mean(`Recommend hospital - star rating`))

data2comp <- data2comp %>%
  pivot_longer(starts_with("mean"), 
               names_to = "Question", 
               values_to = "Rating")

mean_compare_plot <- ggplot(data2comp, aes(State, Rating)) +
  geom_line(aes(group = State), color = "gray40") +
  geom_point(aes(color = Question)) +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Comparison of Mean State Hospital Star Ratings by Patients and CMS",
       subtitle = "Scale: 1 to 5",
       x = "", y = "Star Rating",
       fill = "Rater",
       caption = "Source: https://www.medicare.gov/hospitalcompare/search.html") +
  scale_color_discrete(name = "Rater",
                       breaks = c("mean_rat", "mean_rec"),
                       labels = c("CMS", "Patient")) +
  theme_minimal()

mean_compare_plot

data3filter <- data3 %>% select(`Facility ID`, State, `HCAHPS Question`, 
                                `Patient Survey Star Rating`) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = 'HCAHPS Question',
              values_from = 'Patient Survey Star Rating')

data3comp <- data3filter %>% group_by(State) %>% 
  summarize(`Nurse communication` = mean(`Nurse communication - star rating`), 
            `Doctor communication` = mean(`Doctor communication - star rating`),
            `Staff responsiveness` = mean(`Staff responsiveness - star rating`),
            `Medicine communication` = mean(`Communication about medicines - star rating`),
            `Discharge info` = mean(`Discharge information - star rating`),
            `Care transition` = mean(`Care transition - star rating`),
            `Cleanliness` = mean(`Cleanliness - star rating`),
            `Quietness` = mean(`Quietness - star rating`),
            `Overall hospital rating` = mean(`Overall hospital rating - star rating`),
            `Recommend hospital` = mean(`Recommend hospital - star rating`),
            `Summary rating` = mean(`Summary star rating`))

# plot1 - scatterplot
ggplot(data3comp, aes(x = `Nurse communication`, y = `Summary rating`)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = lm, se = FALSE) +
  coord_fixed()

# plot2 - correlation matrix heatmap from http://www.sthda.com/english/wiki/ggplot2-quick-correlation-matrix-heatmap-r-software-and-data-visualization
cordata <- data3comp[,c(2,3,4,5,6,7,8,9,12)]
cormat <- round(cor(cordata),2)
melted_cormat <- melt(cormat)

ggplot(melted_cormat, aes(x = Var1, y = Var2, fill = value)) +
  geom_tile()

# Get lower triangle of the correlation matrix
  get_lower_tri<-function(cormat){
    cormat[upper.tri(cormat)] <- NA
    return(cormat)
  }
  # Get upper triangle of the correlation matrix
  get_upper_tri <- function(cormat){
    cormat[lower.tri(cormat)]<- NA
    return(cormat)
  }
upper_tri <- get_upper_tri(cormat)
melted_cormat <- melt(upper_tri, na.rm = TRUE)

corplot <- ggplot(data = melted_cormat, aes(Var2, Var1, fill = value)) +
 geom_tile(color = "white") +
 scale_fill_gradient2(low = "blue", high = "red", mid = "white", 
   midpoint = .5, limit = c(0,1), space = "Lab", 
   name="Pearson\nCorrelation") +
 theme_minimal() + 
 theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, 
    size = 12, hjust = 1))+
 coord_fixed() +
  geom_text(aes(Var2, Var1, label = value), color = "black", size = 4) +
 theme(
  axis.title.x = element_blank(),
  axis.title.y = element_blank(),
  panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
  panel.border = element_blank(),
  panel.background = element_blank(),
  axis.ticks = element_blank(),
  legend.justification = c(1, 0),
  legend.position = c(0.6, 0.7),
  legend.direction = "horizontal")+
  guides(fill = guide_colorbar(barwidth = 7, barheight = 1,
                title.position = "top", title.hjust = 0.5)) 
  
corplot

Wow wow wow!! Thanks for sharing your code with, Mike! These are AMAZING drafts! Please see my comments below as per Daniels guidelines.

Strengths

  1. Your plots overall are beautiful! I especially like how logically youve joined your data with the us_states data. This really helped my own anxiety about making maps!
  2. I also like the way youve created separate summarize tbls to use for your plots. I tend to confuse myself with using summarize and creating subsets with select() and mutate(). Your way is much simpler! 3.Your line plot is an excellent way of showing the variance in CMS vs Patient star ratings. It is clear that there is a mismatch across most states.
  3. Your triangle correlation plot is fantastic!! Its very easy to understand and highly intuitive. Really awesome job!

What I learned

  1. From your corplot, I learned that we could fill by value and not just by color. So useful!

Suggestions

  1. My suggestion is regarding your lineplot of star ratings. The aspect ratio combined with the number of states on the plot makes it difficult to compare states with each other. My intial suggestion was to adjust the aspect ratio Ive included some draft code above. I learned that you cant use coord_fixed with coord_flip because they will just undo each other. Also, it seems I cant specify the aspect ratio within theme_minimal so I attempted to recreate the minimal theme manually. After all this, Im not sure how helpful modifying the aspect ratio really is
  2. Another suggestion is regarding the colorscale of your corplot. Though very bright, the colors may not be accessible to all - especially in differentiating between the variations of orange. Perhaps a sequential palette from colorbrewer.org would help!
